{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486976"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:52:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:52:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"222"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/222"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.64,0.07,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"222"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47265"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/222"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"222"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31973"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"260"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"12910"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1610"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11168"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38596"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47265"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of increasing pain and swelling in his left knee. He can no longer weight-bear. He reports competing in a cycling race five days ago, however, does not recall hurting his knee. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His left knee is swollen, warm, and tender with limited range of movement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations will be most important in directing treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound of the knee","Arthrocentesis","Synovial biopsy","Dual energy CT of the knee","Blood cultures"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPatient presentations with one or multiple hot swollen joints is a relatively common medical emergency with diverse differentials. Septic arthritis, which the case stem suggests, is arguably one of the most important differentials to consider, given the high morbidity and mortality associated with the condition. Characteristic features of septic arthritis include a short (few days) history of a hot, restricted, swollen joint and systemic features of infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough the diagnosis is based on clinical findings, in real life this patient will have several investigations undertaken on initial presentation. \u003Cstrong\u003EArthrocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E, the sterile aspiration of synovial fluid, is the investigation of choice to confirm the likely diagnosis. It can determine the presence or absence of bacterial organisms and crystals, thus differentiating between septic arthritis and other acute knee pain differentials. Other investigations that are likely to be performed on initial presentation will include an X-ray and various laboratory studies (full blood count, C-reactive protein, erythrocyte sedimentation rate).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound of the knee\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful where arthrocentesis is unremarkable, however is not indicated for first-line investigation of suspected septic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynovial biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to diagnose septic arthritis - however, is more invasive than arthrocentesis and thus less commonly used.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered to identify the presence of systemic infection and thus guide management; like ultrasound, would be a secondary investigation after arthrocentesis is performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDual-energy CT\u003C/strong\u003E, in which CT images are obtained at two energy spectra, is useful in the diagnosis of gout and pseudo-gout through the detection of calcium or uric acid. The stem describes a case suspicious for septic arthritis, a diagnosis that needs to be urgently excluded before investigating for less concerning diagnoses such as pseudo-gout. Furthermore, examination of samples obtained during arthrocentesis would likely diagnose or refute pseudo gout, and therefore a dual-energy CT would likely not be necessary in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An acute, painful knee joint in the absence of trauma should be assumed to be due to septic arthritis until proven otherwise."],"references":["Mathews C, Weston V, Jones A, Field M, Coakley G. Bacterial septic arthritis in adults. The Lancet. 2010;375(9717):846-855. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(09)61595-6/abstract","Bunt CW, Jonas CE, Chang JG. Knee Pain in adults and adolescents: the initial evaluation. Am Fam Physician. 2018;98(9):576-585. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2018/1101/p576.html","Long B, Koyfman A, Gottlieb M. Evaluation and management of septic arthritis and its mimics in the emergency department. West J Emerg Med. 2019;20(2):331-341. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30881554/","Odedra D, Narayanasamy S, Sabongui S, Priya S, Krishna S, Sheikh A. Dual energy CT physics - a primer for the emergency radiologist. Front Radiol. 2022;2:820430. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37492677/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31973"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"222"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31973"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-19T10:12:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-12T10:21:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"222"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47265"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"up